      "message": "\u003e \u003e \u003e \u003e Ah, I followed arm64 since that was in convenient copy-paste format in the docs.\n\u003e \u003e \u003e \u003e \n\u003e \u003e \u003e \u003e ... Android x86 complained about https://gist.github.com/sgraham/da177684758b758aac86866eb3b05502\n\u003e \u003e \u003e \n\u003e \u003e \u003e Did you update past yesterday’s 5969d6b1eb22?\n\u003e \u003e \n\u003e \u003e Yeah I think I have that. Just tried at 2403d066, and I still get the same error. Quite possible that I messed up something else along the way though.\n\u003e \n\u003e Did you re-gyp after that?\n\u003e \n\u003e Wait, maybe it doesn’t matter:\n\u003e \n\u003e \u003e -D__ANDROID_API__\u003d21 -D_FILE_OFFSET_BITS\u003d64\n\u003e \n\u003e Hmm, that’s not a configuration I tested. I’ll look.\n\nIt turns out that the _FILE_OFFSET_BITS\u003d64 stuff is actually broken until API 24 for off_t-using functions in \u003cstdio.h\u003e.\n\nhttps://github.com/android-ndk/ndk/issues/480\n\nWe don’t actually ever use those interfaces in our own code, but gtest does. I can probably drop _FILE_OFFSET_BITS\u003d64 for just the gtest library build with unified headers before API 24.\n\nIn the mean time, I do all 32-bit testing at API 16, matching what Chrome uses.",
